<subSubSection id="1FE5655FFFE3416ECA81E8DBFAB32207" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE3416ECA81E8DBFD7221B4" blockId="21.[151,1437,367,610]" box="[199,704,439,465]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE3416ECA81E8DBFEE121B4" bold="true" box="[199,339,439,465]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">References:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE3416ECB1CE8DBFD7221B4" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[346,704,439,465]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE3416ECA81E8B7FAB32207" blockId="21.[151,1437,367,610]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE3416ECA81E8B7FED02190" bold="true" box="[199,354,475,501]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE3416ECB9AE8B7FD922190" box="[476,544,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[161,1415,290,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-72@5.[151,1436,273,1718]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left male tegmina of Acanthoplus discoidalis (CH8946), Acanthoproctus cervinus (CH8947), Hetrodes pupus (CHelb8948), Enyaliopsis bloyeti (CH8853), E. carolinus (CH8625), E. ephippiatus (CH7737), E. jennae (damaged; CH8267), Gymnoproctus rammei (CH8763), Eugasteroides loricatus (CH7352), Spalacomimus stettinenesis, S. talpa (CH7354), S. verruciferus (CH7188). Scale 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392715/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file (
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE3416EC8B0E8B7FCF82190" box="[758,842,475,501]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,332,356]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Body dimensions and characteristics of stridulatory files in Hetrodini" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" tableUuid="0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101">Table 1</tableCitation>
) and spectrum of the song do not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE3416ECB38E893FE5B227C" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[382,489,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern. The calling song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE3416EC959E893FCC9227C" box="[799,891,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1776,1800]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,632,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-221@11.[151,1436,597,1753]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Acanthoplus, Gymnoproctus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes (figures of Acanthoplus, Acanthoproctus and Hetrodes based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Acanthoplus discoidalis, B–C Acanthoplus longipes, D Gymnoproctus rammei, E Gymnoproctus sculpturatus, F Gymnoproctus spec., G Acanthoproctus cervinus, H Acanthoproctus diadematus, I Hetrodes pupus. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-mssection)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392729" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392729/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Fig. 7G</figureCitation>
; after 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE3416EC983E893FA81227C" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[965,1331,511,537]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
) consists of long series of syllables (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE3416EC840EB48FD84225B" box="[518,566,548,574]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">type</typeStatus>
B in 
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE3416EC833EB4FFD0B225B" box="[629,697,547,574]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,198,1221]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[151,1436,181,1231]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Oscillograms of song types in Hetrodini. Song consisting A of long trills (Cosmoderus femoralis CH8627), B of broken trills (including transitions to long echemes; B1 Spalacomimus talpa, B2 Enyaliopsis jennae, B3 Enyaliopsis ephippiatus) or C of regularly repeated echemes (C1 Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, C2 Eugaster guyoni). 1-min-sections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392721/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). The SRR is unusually low for 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE3416ECE61EB4FFB202258" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[1063,1170,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
and the syllables much longer than in the other genera (
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE3416ECBBBEB2BFCDA2204" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[509,872,583,609]" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
; see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE3416EC9D8EB2BFC402204" box="[926,1010,583,609]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
) except in 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE3416ECE28EB2BFB482204" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1873" box="[1134,1274,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Acanthoplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="472" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE3416ECE28EB2BFB482204" box="[1134,1274,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="472">Acanthoplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
